50|$|Inflatable {{structures}} and inflatable buildings {{are used in}} many ways including membrane roofs and covers, sails, buildings and pavilions, airships, furniture, airspace structures, boats, <b>escape</b> <b>slides,</b> security mattresses, swimming pools, coverings, games and castles, air bags and many other applications. Examples include an inflatable church and an inflatable pub.|$|R
50|$|On 15 January 1962, A3D-2 (A-3B) BuNo 142243, {{assigned}} to Heavy Attack Squadron ONE (VAH-1), crashed near NAS Sanford following an in-flight emergency. Despite a malfunction of the <b>escape</b> <b>slide,</b> all crewmen bailed out safely.|$|E
50|$|An {{evacuation}} slide is an inflatable slide used to evacuate an aircraft quickly. An <b>escape</b> <b>slide</b> is required on all commercial (passenger carrying) aircraft where the door sill height is such that, {{in the event}} of an evacuation, passengers would be unable to step down from the door uninjured (Federal Aviation Administration requires slides on all aircraft doors where the floor is 6 ft or more above the ground).|$|E
